<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1627,2041]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,389,1627,1654]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Generic characters.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[479,551,1627,1654]" captionStart="FIGURES 2‒3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1673,1698]" captionTargetBox="[184,1414,181,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1414,181,1648]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 2‒3. Nosphistica subrectangula sp. nov. 2. adult, holotype, ♂; 3. male genitalia, paratype, slide No. LSR13160. Scales: 2=2mm, 3=0.5 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386921/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
): Antenna as long as or longer than forewing, flagellum in male ciliate ventrally, becoming weak toward apex. Labial palpus with second segment thickened, third segment slender, strongly upturned. Forewing with well-developed discocellular stigma; hindwing with area between 3A and dorsum dark brown or blackish brown, often interrupted medially by a white marking. Venation: forewing with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1287,1295,1751,1765]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1370,1378,1751,1765]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">2</subScript>
free, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[170,178,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">3</subScript>
stalked with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[346,371,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">4+5</subScript>
, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[403,411,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">5</subScript>
usually stalked with R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[666,674,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">4</subScript>
, or absent (as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1911" box="[864,986,1769,1794]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Nosphistica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erratica">
<emphasis box="[864,986,1769,1794]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">N. erratica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1034,1042,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1121,1129,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">2</subScript>
present, M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1255,1263,1786,1800]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">3</subScript>
usually stalked with CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[262,287,1821,1835]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1+2</subScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[304,385,1803,1830]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1334,1359]" captionTargetBox="[174,1408,831,1303]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[169,1418,821,1309]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Wing venation of Nosphistica species. a. N. grandiunca sp. nov., slide No. YS17136; b. N. paramecola, slide No. YS17108. Scales=2 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386925/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Fig. 5a</figureCitation>
), sometimes absent (
<figureCitation box="[623,707,1803,1830]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1334,1359]" captionTargetBox="[174,1408,831,1303]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[169,1418,821,1309]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Wing venation of Nosphistica species. a. N. grandiunca sp. nov., slide No. YS17136; b. N. paramecola, slide No. YS17108. Scales=2 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386925/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Fig. 5b</figureCitation>
), CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[782,790,1821,1835]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[899,907,1821,1835]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">2</subScript>
stalked; hindwing with Rs and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1293,1301,1821,1835]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
stalked, M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1428,1436,1821,1835]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">2</subScript>
present, or absent (as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1918" box="[428,561,1839,1865]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Philoptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="effrenata">
<emphasis box="[428,561,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">N. effrenata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[611,619,1856,1870]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[728,736,1856,1870]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
stalked, CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[891,899,1856,1870]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">2</subScript>
remote from M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1080,1088,1856,1870]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">3</subScript>
+CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1157,1165,1856,1870]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">1</subScript>
at base. Abdominal tergites with dense spiniform setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="499" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1627,2041]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
<emphasis box="[199,365,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[382,452,1909,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 2‒3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1673,1698]" captionTargetBox="[184,1414,181,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[174,1414,181,1648]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 2‒3. Nosphistica subrectangula sp. nov. 2. adult, holotype, ♂; 3. male genitalia, paratype, slide No. LSR13160. Scales: 2=2mm, 3=0.5 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386921/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Uncus represented by a sclerotized plate. Gnathos with lateral arms broadly banded, sometimes forming a basal plate by fused medially. Costal bar conspicuously free of valva basally. Juxta large, exceeding middle of tegumen posteriorly, weakly sclerotized or membranous distally, produced anteromedially; lateral process varied in shape and size.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386921/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="499" startId="2.[151,264,1673,1698]" targetBox="[184,1414,181,1635]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1673,1734]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,317,1673,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">FIGURES 2‒3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Yu &amp; Wang, 2019" authorityName="Yu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2019" box="[325,597,1674,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Nosphistica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subrectangula" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[325,597,1674,1698]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">Nosphistica subrectangula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[606,689,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[606,689,1674,1698]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
2. adult, holotype, ♂; 3. male genitalia, paratype, slide No. LSR13160. Scales: 2=2mm, 3=0.5 mm
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1780,1986]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis box="[199,393,1780,1806]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[411,484,1780,1806]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1762,1787]" captionTargetBox="[350,1216,181,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[340,1247,181,1737]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 4. Female genitalia of N. subrectangula sp. nov., paratype, slide No. YS17140. Scale=0.5 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3386923/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Abdominal sternite VIII usually concave medially on posterior margin. Apophyses anteriores shorter than apophyses posteriores. Corpus bursae elliptical or ovate; signum varied in number and shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="499" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1780,1986]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1888,1915]" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1911" box="[327,459,1888,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Nosphistica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="499" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[327,459,1888,1914]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="499">Nosphistica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other genera of this family by the flagellum of the antenna only ciliate ventrally in the male, the area between 3A and dorsum of the hindwing dark brown or blackish brown; and the costal bar in the male genitalia conspicuously free of the valva basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
